AlignDiff: Learning Physically-Grounded Camera Alignment via Diffusion

Liuyue Xie1*, Jiancong Guo2, Ozan Cakmakci2, Andre Araujo3, László A. Jeni1, Zhiheng Jia2
1Carnegie Mellon University    2Google    3Google DeepMind
*This work was done as part of a Google internship. Currently at Amazon AGI.
Paper arXiv Code (Coming Soon)

AlignDiff can be used to provide undistorted images and camera poses for downstream tasks such as Gaussian Splatting 3D reconstruction.

Abstract

Accurate camera calibration is a fundamental task for 3D perception, especially when dealing with real-world, in-the-wild environments where complex optical distortions are common. Existing methods often rely on pre-rectified images or calibration patterns, which limits their applicability and flexibility. In this work, we introduce a novel framework that addresses these challenges by jointly modeling camera intrinsic and extrinsic parameters using a generic ray camera model. Our approach directly handles fine-grained local distortions from raw images without requiring pre-processing. We propose AlignDiff, a diffusion model conditioned on geometric priors, enabling the simultaneous estimation of camera distortions and scene geometry. To enhance distortion prediction, we incorporate edge-aware attention, focusing the model on geometric features around image edges, rather than semantic content. Furthermore, to enhance generalizability to real-world captures, we incorporate a large database of ray-traced lenses containing over three thousand samples. This database characterizes the distortion inherent in a diverse variety of lens forms. Our experiments demonstrate that the proposed method significantly reduces angular error of estimated ray bundles by ~+8.2° and overall calibration accuracy, outperforming existing approaches on challenging, real-world datasets. We will publicly release our code and data to facilitate further research in this direction upon acceptance.

AlignDiff recovers lens ray profiles from a sequence of images.

Related Links

This work is inspired by many recent works in the field of end-to-end camera pose estimation and undistortion pattern estimation.

PoseDiffusion introduces a diffusion model to estimate the rotation, translation from multi-view images.

RayRegression, RayDiffusion, WildCamera and DiffCalib all use ray camera representation to express the projective relationship with each pixel to the 3D scene.

We extent the camera ray representation to aberrated lens designs, and ground the learning on geometric cues. We show that the estimated camera rays can be recovered for poses and aberration profile.
